Use `Request.BodyReader` (or `Request.Body`) to stream multipart sections directly to disk, bypassing the default buffering. Here's the approach:

**1. Disable form size limits on the endpoint:**

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Not a multipart request");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            || !cd.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize!
        var path = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var fs = File.Create(path);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);
    }

    return Results.Ok("Uploaded");
})
.DisableAntiforgery()
.WithMetadata(new DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute());
```

**2. Raise Kestrel's max request body size in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(k =>
{
    k.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});
```

**3. Required usings:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;
```

**Why this works:**

| | `IFormFile` | `MultipartReader` |
|---|---|---|
| Buffering | Entire file in memory (or temp) | Streams chunk-by-chunk (~80 KB) |
| Memory | O(file size) | O(buffer size) |
| 2 GB file | OOM / crash | ~constant memory |

**Key points:**

- `MultipartReader` reads one buffer at a time — never holds the full file in memory.
- `DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute` removes the default 30 MB cap.
- Don't bind `[FromForm]` or `IFormFile` — that triggers the model binder's buffering.
- Sanitize filenames from `ContentDisposition` to prevent path traversal.
